ma, who's that at the door?
It's a package for me
by special messenger.

01:08.100 --> 01:11.870
Ooh, it looks exciting.
Who's it from?
It don't say.

01:11.937 --> 01:15.306
I wonder what it can be.
Open it up.

01:15.374 --> 01:18.442
The last time
I had a package this size...

01:18.510 --> 01:21.612
Was from your grandmother
on your father's side--

01:21.681 --> 01:26.584
a beautiful lace tablecloth
over 80 years old.

01:26.652 --> 01:31.355
I don't remember seeing that.
That's because I've been
saving it for best.

01:31.423 --> 01:34.559
But we ain't had no best.

01:34.626 --> 01:38.797
Open up the package.
What do you think it is, Gloria?

01:38.864 --> 01:42.834
Ma, if you don't open it up,
I'll go crazy.
Right.

01:42.902 --> 01:44.936
Oh, it's a beautiful box.

01:45.004 --> 01:48.940
I'm gonna save it.
It'll come in hand--

01:49.008 --> 01:54.245
oh, Gloria,
this can't be for me.

01:54.313 --> 01:58.049
It's a mink cape.
It's beautiful.

01:58.117 --> 02:02.353
You know, I've seen this
somewhere before.

02:02.421 --> 02:04.823
Oh, there must be
some mistake.

02:04.890 --> 02:08.193
No, ma. It's no mistake.
It's from your cousin Amelia.

02:08.259 --> 02:13.131
Amelia. That's where
I've seen it, on Amelia.

02:15.367 --> 02:18.970
But why would she be
sending me her mink cape?

02:19.038 --> 02:20.972
"Dear Edith,
I'm giving this to you...

02:21.040 --> 02:24.909
Because of your kindness
in looking after me
after I had my operation."

02:24.977 --> 02:28.079
Oh, she didn't have to do that.

02:28.147 --> 02:31.249
"I know you'll say I
don't have to do this, Edith,

02:31.316 --> 02:33.718
but I really want you
to have the mink."

02:33.786 --> 02:36.287
Oh, ain't that nice?

02:36.355 --> 02:39.758
I wonder why she sent it.
They're coming over on Friday.

02:39.825 --> 02:44.562
"I know we're coming over
Friday, but I couldn't
wait for you to have it."

02:44.630 --> 02:49.868
Oh, that's very nice.
But what will Amelia
do without it?

02:49.935 --> 02:53.471
"Russ is buying me a new one
for my birthday anyway.

02:53.538 --> 02:56.074
Love, Amelia."
Oh, ma, put it on.

02:56.142 --> 03:00.645
You know,
I've always wondered
what mink felt like.

03:00.712 --> 03:02.647
What does it feel like, ma?

03:02.714 --> 03:07.718
It feels just like soft fur.

03:09.621 --> 03:11.555
<i>[ Door opens ]</i>
<i>[ Michael ]</i>
<i>Hi, Gloria. I'm home.</i>

03:11.623 --> 03:14.192
Oh, ma, that's Michael.
You stay in here
until I call you.

03:14.260 --> 03:17.361
Hi, sweetheart.
I'm glad you're home.
Hi.

03:17.429 --> 03:20.298
Stand right there.
I've got a big surprise for you.
What's going on?

03:20.365 --> 03:22.700
You'll see.
Ready, ma?
Yeah.

03:23.769 --> 03:26.304
¶ There she is ¶

03:26.371 --> 03:31.109
¶ miss America ¶

03:31.177 --> 03:34.145
<i>¶ there she is ¶</i>

03:34.213 --> 03:37.581
<i>¶ your ideal ¶</i>

03:37.649 --> 03:41.352
<i>¶ there she is ¶</i>

03:41.420 --> 03:44.923
I don't believe it, ma.
It can't be you.

03:44.990 --> 03:47.425
Oh, yeah, Mike.
It's me.

03:47.492 --> 03:49.627
Ma, that's mink.
Where did that come from?

03:49.695 --> 03:53.798
It's Amelia dekuyper's way
of saying thank you.
Gee, that's some thank you.

03:53.866 --> 03:59.237
I'm gonna have to find
someplace fancy to wear this.

03:59.305 --> 04:03.674
Only Archie don't take me
to no mink places.

04:03.742 --> 04:07.411
Archie don't take you
to no places.

04:07.479 --> 04:09.914
Oh, Mike.
That ain't fair.

04:09.982 --> 04:13.852
It's true,
but it ain't fair.

04:13.919 --> 04:19.357
I gotta see
what this looks like
in the bathroom door.

04:19.423 --> 04:22.593
That's something.
I didn't know cousin
Amelia was that rich.

04:22.661 --> 04:24.963
Well, her husband's
a plumbing contractor.

04:25.030 --> 04:29.000
Oh, yeah.
They make half a mink a day.

04:29.068 --> 04:31.002
Boy, I wanna tell you.

04:31.070 --> 04:34.605
Coming home through this city
some nights is like coming
through a minefield.

04:34.673 --> 04:38.009
Daddy, you should see
what ma just got.
I'm talking, Gloria.

04:39.611 --> 04:41.545
I leave work and
I go down the subway, see.

04:41.613 --> 04:45.483
Your mayor Lindsay's
two-level trolley system.

04:45.550 --> 04:48.552
And what do I find there?
The subway platform
is jammed with peoples.

04:48.620 --> 04:53.291
It's a wall-to-wall melting pot.
Why? 'Cause the trains ain't
running again.

04:53.359 --> 04:56.494
Well, that's too bad--
so, looking for somebody
who speaks my language,

04:56.561 --> 04:58.696
I go up to this subway guard.

04:58.764 --> 05:01.966
And he happens to be one of your
pushy "imported" ricans.

05:04.336 --> 05:07.638
And so I says to him,
you know, trying to be polite,

05:07.706 --> 05:10.008
"what's up, Pedro?"

05:13.212 --> 05:15.746
He says, "the main's broke.
The water's flooding the rails."

05:15.814 --> 05:19.650
"How am I gonna get home?"
He says, "try swimming
up the tracks."

05:20.986 --> 05:24.188
Now I ask you, for a city
employee to talk to an--

05:24.256 --> 05:26.724
I'm all alone here.
When did this happen?

05:26.792 --> 05:30.361
What, are you hiding someplace?
Where the hell are you?

05:30.429 --> 05:32.931
What's going on?
Daddy, you just stand
right there, okay?

05:32.998 --> 05:34.933
Where's your mother?

05:35.000 --> 05:37.835
