11:33.124 --> 11:35.593
The dry cleaners is only
two blocks away here.

11:35.661 --> 11:39.297
You know, when I think of you
making her give back that fur,
I get sick to my stomach.

11:41.600 --> 11:43.834
Look at you. You could eat
the carpets off the floor...

11:43.902 --> 11:46.637
Without getting
sick to your stomach.

11:47.939 --> 11:50.808
Michael.
Ma got those goodies
for Russ and Amelia.

11:50.875 --> 11:53.243
Besides, we're going
to eat after the movie.

11:53.312 --> 11:57.014
Oh, my.
Sorry I took so long.

11:57.081 --> 12:01.786
Oh, let me catch my breath.
Never mind about your breath.
You can breathe later.

12:01.853 --> 12:05.656
Russ and Amelia are coming
over here any minute, huh?
Where's the cape?

12:05.724 --> 12:07.658
They're keeping it.

12:07.726 --> 12:11.395
The jeffersons have been
cleaning that cape for six days.
Ain't they done yet?

12:11.463 --> 12:14.432
He had terrible trouble
with that stain.

12:14.499 --> 12:18.436
He had to put
the mink through twice
and it still wouldn't come out.

12:18.503 --> 12:20.604
Well, he should have
put it through a third time.

12:20.672 --> 12:23.073
That's just it.
He shouldn't have.
The third time,

12:23.141 --> 12:27.345
the fur came out
in big patches.

12:27.412 --> 12:30.848
Are you telling me that
Jefferson ruined that fur?
Edith, I'll sue the guy.

12:30.915 --> 12:32.850
He was very upset about it,

12:32.917 --> 12:37.455
but he says that he'll
get his insurance company
to clear it right away.

12:37.522 --> 12:40.391
Why did you bring it
down to the jeffersons'
in the first place?

12:40.459 --> 12:43.527
I mean, the colored people
don't know nothing
about dry cleaning.

12:43.595 --> 12:46.063
What do they know about fur?

12:46.130 --> 12:49.967
That's right, arch.
All we taught them was
how to work with cotton.

12:55.940 --> 12:58.676
Go carry a sign, will ya?

13:00.645 --> 13:05.215
Mr. Jefferson said
we might get as much as $300.

13:05.283 --> 13:10.755
Edith, don't never bring
no more clean-- $300?

13:10.822 --> 13:15.860
Yeah, he said it would be that
because it was not new fur.

13:15.927 --> 13:18.662
Well, wait a minute.
Edith, $300?

13:18.730 --> 13:20.798
Hey, wait a second, arch.

13:20.866 --> 13:23.033
You're not thinking of keeping
that money, are you?

13:23.101 --> 13:25.369
I might be.

13:27.038 --> 13:30.508
- Why not?
- You already told Russ you
were gonna give back the cape.

13:30.575 --> 13:32.476
But there ain't no cape now.

13:32.544 --> 13:35.746
Oh, gee, arch.
When it was just a fur cape,
you couldn't care less.

13:35.814 --> 13:38.783
Now it's $300,
your whole world lights up.

13:38.850 --> 13:40.984
Would you listen to this guy?
You know something
about yourself?

13:41.052 --> 13:43.153
You ain't got
no class at all.

13:43.221 --> 13:45.723
What do you expect me to do,
insult a relation,

13:45.791 --> 13:50.528
a rich relation at that,
by offering him $300?

13:50.595 --> 13:52.897
Arch, I thought
you didn't wanna take charity.

13:52.964 --> 13:56.767
This ain't charity.
This is gonna be a check
from an insurance company.

13:56.835 --> 13:59.269
And if you think insurance
companies give out charity,

13:59.337 --> 14:01.906
you're a lot dumber
than I ever gave you credit for.

14:01.973 --> 14:05.709
Archie, it's the dekuypers'
money because it was their
cape that got damaged.

14:05.777 --> 14:07.812
How can you honestly
think of keeping the money?

14:07.879 --> 14:12.115
The same way a lot of people
keep millions of dollars,
don't pay no taxes.

14:12.183 --> 14:15.319
Like, uh, for instance
your Ronald Reagan there.

14:17.622 --> 14:20.491
You're throwing
that example up to me?

14:22.594 --> 14:26.630
Certainly, meathead.
That is the way the system
is supposed to work.

14:26.698 --> 14:30.133
And Reagan is a guy
who knows how to work it.

14:30.201 --> 14:33.203
Archie, that's not the way
the system's supposed to work.

14:33.271 --> 14:35.539
I told you about Ronald Reagan,
you bawled hell out of me...

14:35.607 --> 14:37.541
For besmirching the name
of a great governor.

14:37.609 --> 14:40.077
And don't do it no more.

14:42.180 --> 14:45.282
Because the U.S. of a. Is run
along certain principles.

14:45.350 --> 14:48.018
And giving back $300
to a man who don't need it...

14:48.086 --> 14:51.154
Goes against everything
this nation stands for.

14:51.222 --> 14:54.525
If that's what this nation
stands for, then the people have
been devalued, not the dollar.

14:54.593 --> 14:56.326
Nuts to you.
Yeah?

14:56.394 --> 14:58.328
You was supposed to be
going to the movies. Get lost.

14:58.396 --> 15:00.831
Come on, Michael.
Let's go.
<i>[ Doorbell rings ]</i>

15:00.899 --> 15:03.968
<i>I don't want them going</i>
<i>out the front door.</i>
<i>Go out the back door.</i>

15:04.035 --> 15:06.570
Why? What's wrong?
Because I don't want youse
to meet the dekuyper's...

15:06.638 --> 15:08.706
And open your big mouth
and screw everything up.

15:08.773 --> 15:10.841
You're nuts.
Go on. Get lost.

15:10.909 --> 15:12.843
<i>[ Doorbell rings ]</i>
<i>Coming.</i>

15:12.911 --> 15:15.980
Hold it, Edith.
Don't answer that door.
Just a minute.

15:16.047 --> 15:20.350
Now, say nothing.
Don't you open your mouth and
say word one about that cape.

15:20.418 --> 15:23.086
You make like
an oyster and clam up.

15:23.154 --> 15:26.390
I hate these people.
Open that door.

15:28.126 --> 15:31.461
Hi, Edith.
Hey, how are you?

15:32.998 --> 15:35.465
Hey, Russ.
How are you?
Good.

15:35.534 --> 15:38.035
Amelia.
Oh, Archie.

15:38.102 --> 15:41.805
You look terrific.
You put a few pounds on,
but you look terrific.

15:41.873 --> 15:44.675
Arch, you ain't changed a bit.
Same old arch.

15:44.743 --> 15:47.277
Same old Russ.
Same old Edith too.

15:47.345 --> 15:49.346
Same old living room.

15:49.414 --> 15:51.515
Sort of brown, ain't it?

15:51.583 --> 15:54.184
Reminds me
of what I come up from.

15:54.252 --> 15:57.054
[ No audible dialog ]

16:02.894 --> 16:07.431
Arch, what Russ means
is we're more like
what you'd call pink people.

16:07.498 --> 16:11.101
Aw, hey.
We got a son-in-law
who's one of them.

16:11.169 --> 16:14.137
Hey, come on, Amelia.
Sit down on the sofa here.

16:14.205 --> 16:16.139
You do the decorating
yourself, Edith?

16:16.207 --> 16:20.578
Oh, no, no. I ain't
too good at that, Amelia.

16:20.645 --> 16:25.482
But I did paint
the laundry basket once
with one of them spray cans.

16:25.550 --> 16:28.185
Remember, Archie?
Yeah, forget it.

16:28.252 --> 16:31.789
But I-- I forgot
to take the laundry out.

16:34.492 --> 16:39.663
And Archie was wearing
wicker pattern underwear
for a whole year.

16:39.731 --> 16:42.365
Private, Edith, huh?
Private.

16:43.702 --> 16:45.636
Hey, arch,
about that mink cape.

16:45.704 --> 16:47.605
Cape?
Wh-what about it?

16:47.672 --> 16:51.909
I don't believe none of that
guff you was giving me
about Edith's allergies.

16:51.977 --> 16:54.979
It was only you being
allergic to charity, wasn't it?

16:55.046 --> 16:57.147
Russ, I never
thought of that as charity.

16:57.215 --> 16:59.149
What do you mean?
Coming from you?

16:59.217 --> 17:03.821
Good. Because Amelia and me,
we want Edith to keep the cape.

17:03.888 --> 17:09.660
Why shouldn't she have
a little luxury in her life?
I mean, look around here.

17:09.728 --> 17:12.429
- Russel.
- Listen, Amelia.
Listen. That's okay.

17:12.497 --> 17:16.000
I mean, after all,
some guys make it
and some guys don't.

17:16.067 --> 17:20.537
So youse two wanna give
that fur cape to Edith here,
well, I say beautiful.

17:20.605 --> 17:23.573
- But Archie,
how can we keep the cape?
- Beautiful.

17:23.642 --> 17:25.575
Beautiful.

17:29.014 --> 17:31.949
Is there something in your eye?

17:36.287 --> 17:38.455
Would you make coffee?

17:38.523 --> 17:42.726
Wait a minute, Edith.
First I gotta see what
you look like in that fur.

17:42.794 --> 17:45.863
- Try it on.
- Oh, Amelia, I-I--

17:45.930 --> 17:48.165
she, uh, she can't
do that, Amelia, see?

17:48.232 --> 17:51.035
'Cause the cape is
still at the dry cleaners.

17:51.102 --> 17:54.004
But I had it cleaned just
before I sent it to you.

17:54.072 --> 17:56.540
Oh, well, uh, you know,
Edith done it again...

17:56.607 --> 17:59.409
Because she's a nut about
bringing things to the cleaner--
but, Archie, we both took it--

17:59.477 --> 18:02.680
let me finish.

18:02.747 --> 18:05.783
See, Edith knows
these colored people.
They run the dry cleaners.

18:05.850 --> 18:08.185
- Colored?
- Yeah. Oh, hey.

18:08.252 --> 18:11.254
But, listen, they're great.
Didn't you ever hear?

18:11.322 --> 18:14.992
I mean, they get right in there.
The benzine, it don't do
nothing to them there.

18:17.896 --> 18:19.830
I mean, they're
really great at doing furs.

18:19.898 --> 18:21.932
They're real geniuses
in the cleaning profession.

18:22.000 --> 18:24.802
Speaking of clean, arch.
Where's your bathroom?

18:24.869 --> 18:26.804
Oh, same old place, Russ.
Right upstairs.

18:26.871 --> 18:29.206
I don't know why you don't
get a downstairs John.

18:29.273 --> 18:33.077
Well, listen, I ain't got
your money there, buddy.
[ Chuckles ]

18:33.144 --> 18:36.013
You know, there is one thing
that I like about you, arch.

18:36.081 --> 18:39.516
What's that, Russ?
You are poor and you know it.

18:42.954 --> 18:46.757
Just don't wanna throw money
down the drain, right?
[ Chuckles ]

18:46.825 --> 18:48.759
You get it?
Down the drain.

18:48.827 --> 18:50.761
[ Laughing ]

18:50.829 --> 18:55.733
That's a plumber's joke.
Oh, yeah. Plumber.

18:55.800 --> 18:58.168
That's funny.
That's funny.

18:58.236 --> 19:00.537
Laugh it up.

19:03.274 --> 19:05.642
[ Continues laughing ]

19:05.710 --> 19:07.644
Oh, that Russ.

19:07.712 --> 19:09.880
He's always saying
funny things like that.

19:09.948 --> 19:14.417
Working with him
all day long is like having
your own personal Johnny Carson.

19:14.485 --> 19:17.654
[ Toilet flushes ]

19:21.092 --> 19:23.493
Shut the door, Russel.

19:28.432 --> 19:33.336
The door is shut, Amelia.
It always sounds like that.

19:33.404 --> 19:36.673
Hey, arch.
Your float valve is half shut.
Huh?

19:36.741 --> 19:39.743
Oh, yeah. You know,
you could use a new toilet.
Oh.

19:39.811 --> 19:42.345
As a matter of fact, you could
use a whole new bathroom.

19:42.413 --> 19:45.916
<i>[ Doorbell rings ]</i>
<i>Here. Try this.</i>

19:45.984 --> 19:50.287
Thanks very much, Russ.
Will you stop carrying greasy
parts around in your good suit?

19:50.354 --> 19:52.756
Hello, Edith.
Hello, Louise.
Come in.

19:52.824 --> 19:54.892
Oh, you've got company.
I won't stay.

19:54.959 --> 19:58.361
Oh, no. Come and meet
my cousin, Amelia dekuyper.

19:58.429 --> 20:01.564
And this is her husband,
Mr. Russ dekuyper.
Hi, there.

20:01.632 --> 20:05.102
This is Mrs. Jefferson.
Her husband runs the cleaners.

20:05.170 --> 20:09.773
Uh, Mrs. Jefferson,
could we talk to you about all
of this just a little later on?

20:09.841 --> 20:14.077
Oh, sure. But I was just
so upset about what happened
to the mink cape.

20:14.145 --> 20:18.481
-Something happened to the cape?
-It sure was a shame you spilt
all of that sauce on it.

20:18.549 --> 20:21.484
Mrs. Jefferson,
I'll tell you what you do.
Just don't worry about it...

20:21.552 --> 20:24.421
And get us back
the cape as soon as
ever you can, huh?

20:24.488 --> 20:26.924
But there's nothing left
but the skin.

20:29.694 --> 20:34.031
So I got George to make out
his check without waiting for
the insurance to come through.

20:34.098 --> 20:38.601
Just like I told you,
Edith, $300.
Thank you.

20:38.669 --> 20:40.871
Well, so long, folks.
Nice to have met you.
Yeah, yeah.

20:40.939 --> 20:43.140
Thanks very much,
Mrs. Jefferson.
Good-bye there.

20:43.208 --> 20:45.142
Put that away.

20:45.210 --> 20:47.677
Uh, Edith, why don't you make
some coffee for everybody?

20:47.745 --> 20:49.880
Now, wait a second.
What's this about $300?

20:49.948 --> 20:52.950
- Russ, let her make the coffee.
- What about the $300?

20:53.017 --> 20:56.887
Russ, Amelia,
we was gonna tell you.

20:56.955 --> 21:01.825
You see, we had
an accident with the cape
and spilled some food on it.

21:01.893 --> 21:06.830
And the cleaners ruined it.
But the insurance
is paying for it.

21:06.898 --> 21:09.699
Well, well, well.
It's like I always say, Amelia.

21:09.767 --> 21:13.036
Cast your bread upon the waters
and it comes back dough.

21:13.104 --> 21:15.705
Thank you, Edith.
Hold it. Hold it there, Russ.

21:15.773 --> 21:17.707
That check ain't yours.
That's ours.

21:17.775 --> 21:21.144
No, it isn't.
No. He's right, Russel.
We gave them the cape.

21:21.212 --> 21:24.014
Will you zip it up, Amelia.
I want that money.

21:24.082 --> 21:28.518
Listen to rich
daddy drainpipes over here.

21:30.889 --> 21:33.757
Dredging after a lousy $300.

21:33.824 --> 21:35.759
We do not need
the money, Russel.

21:35.826 --> 21:39.429
You know how much
I gotta make to keep
$300 cash in our tax bracket?

21:39.497 --> 21:41.999
I gotta make 800, maybe $1000.

21:42.066 --> 21:45.668
That's why I want that check.
Now, you give me that $1000.

21:45.736 --> 21:49.907
Why, you copper-plated phony,
you. You're money nuts.

21:49.974 --> 21:52.409
When this was just a raggy fur,
you couldn't care less about it.

21:52.476 --> 21:57.080
Now it's $300,
your whole world lights up.
You bet it does.

21:57.148 --> 22:01.718
You really bet it does.
Three hundred bucks tax free
is really illuminating.

22:01.786 --> 22:03.887
And I ain't leaving here
without I get that check.

22:03.955 --> 22:07.224
Oh, money, money, money.
You really love it,
don't you, rich man?

22:07.292 --> 22:11.361
You bet I do.
How do you think
I got to be rich, poor man?

22:11.429 --> 22:16.033
Aw, geez, the greed of him.
I can smell it all over him.
Whoo!

22:16.100 --> 22:19.970
What you're smelling
is the sweet perfume
of success.

22:20.038 --> 22:22.705
Listen to this guy
talking about perfume.

22:22.773 --> 22:26.176
And him all day long
up to his armpits in toilets.

22:31.382 --> 22:35.052
Them toilets got me
my beachfront home
in neponset.

22:35.119 --> 22:37.087
Oh, listen to the big shot here.

22:37.155 --> 22:40.991
Bragging because he was
lucky enough to marry into
a successful plumbing racket.

22:41.059 --> 22:44.928
Successful? Her father's
business wasn't worth the red
ink it cost to keep the books.

22:44.996 --> 22:47.297
I built that business up myself.

22:47.365 --> 22:49.933
Get out of here. Her old man
left you a going concern.

22:50.001 --> 22:51.935
And her brother
on the board of education,

22:52.003 --> 22:54.804
he gave you the concession for
a whole school district there.

22:54.872 --> 22:59.276
Six hundred toilets.
Boy, talk about falling
into a royal flush.

23:03.581 --> 23:06.249
Nobody made me but me!

23:06.317 --> 23:09.252
You tell him, Amelia.
Tell him who built
that business up.

23:09.320 --> 23:12.255
Papa, Freddy,
my Uncle Charlie.

23:12.323 --> 23:15.125
- Will you stop it?
- <i>Oh, listen to that!</i>

23:15.193 --> 23:18.728
Your own wife knows you
for the phony you are. Well,
you ain't getting this check.

23:18.796 --> 23:21.931
This check belongs to us.
No, it don't, Archie.

23:22.000 --> 23:25.369
What are you talking about?
Mrs. Jefferson gave you
this check,

23:25.436 --> 23:27.371
and it says right on the check,

23:27.438 --> 23:30.707
"pay to the order
of Amelia dekuyper."

23:30.774 --> 23:34.111
Amelia dekuyp--
what's her name
doing on this check?

23:34.178 --> 23:36.679
Well, she's the owner
of the mink.

23:36.747 --> 23:41.118
You said yourself, Archie.
As soon as it was cleaned
it had to go back to Amelia...

23:41.185 --> 23:45.055
'Cause you didn't
want no charity
coming into this house.

23:45.123 --> 23:47.057
Edith.
Thank you.
Come along, Amelia.

23:47.125 --> 23:49.059
You see what you done here?

23:49.127 --> 23:51.061
Russ, you ain't
leaving this house...

23:51.129 --> 23:53.663
Till I finish saying to you
what I wanna say to you.

23:53.731 --> 23:56.133
What do you wanna say to me?

23:56.200 --> 23:58.235
I'll split that with you.

23:58.302 --> 24:01.438
Come on, Amelia.
Russ, Russ, don't you walk
out of here with that check.

24:01.506 --> 24:06.543
Russ, if you leave this
house with that there
check there, Russ,

24:06.610 --> 24:09.179
it ain't gonna do
our friendship no good.

24:10.981 --> 24:14.251
<i>[ Car starts, pulls away ]</i>

24:23.694 --> 24:27.030
Once again,
your side of the family.

24:33.204 --> 24:37.074
Come on, daddy,
stop sulking about Russ.

24:37.141 --> 24:40.110
Boy, no wonder they say that
money's the root of all evil.

24:40.178 --> 24:42.112
Yeah, that's right, arch.

24:42.180 --> 24:44.847
Russ only did unto you what
you were trying to do to him.

24:45.916 --> 24:48.285
And remember,
the Bible also says...

24:48.352 --> 24:51.654
It is more blessed
to give than to receive.

24:57.795 --> 25:00.464
I got one for you.

25:00.531 --> 25:02.865
Silence is golden.

25:04.535 --> 25:07.537
So stifle thyself, will you.

25:25.289 --> 25:30.026
[ Announcer ]
All in the family <i>was recorded</i>
<i>on tape before a live audience.</i>

